Predictive analysis of Traffic collision risks¶

DS1 : group 1¶

  • Wejdene Chandoul

  • Achref Khemiri

Problematic¶

In the last few years Artificial Intelligence has found its way to several fields of application of our daily life.

We stumbled upon this article which talks about a Machine Learning project whose goal is to predict the number of accidents over the next two hours in Los Angeles to improve road traffic management.

We found the idea very promising and with great potential for every single city in the world, if we could predict the number of accidents that are going to happen in a certain day , the authorities could deal with them a lot better .

Roger Thayne, former Chief Executive of the Staffordshire Ambulance Service has advised the BBC that potentially around 2,500 lives a year are being lost as a result of delayed ambulance response times and the inability to resuscitate patients at the scene. source

Business Objectives¶

  • Identify what makes a commune more prone to accidents
  • Prevent future deaths caused by ambulance delays

Data Science goals¶

  • realize a feature importance study on our model to tell what makes a commune have the most accidents
  • predict number of future accidents

lieux = pd.DataFrame()
usagers = pd.DataFrame()
vehicules = pd.DataFrame()
caracteristiques = pd.DataFrame()

def read_year(year):
    global lieux
    global usagers
    global vehicules
    global caracteristiques
    l = pd.read_csv(f'data/lieux-{year}.csv',encoding = "ISO-8859-1",low_memory=False)
    u = pd.read_csv(f'data/usagers-{year}.csv',encoding = "ISO-8859-1",low_memory=False)
    v = pd.read_csv(f'data/vehicules-{year}.csv',encoding = "ISO-8859-1",low_memory=False)
    c = pd.read_csv(f'data/caracteristiques-{year}.csv',encoding = "ISO-8859-1",low_memory=False)
    lieux = pd.concat([lieux,l],ignore_index=True)
    usagers = pd.concat([usagers,u],ignore_index=True)
    vehicules = pd.concat([vehicules,v],ignore_index=True)
    caracteristiques = pd.concat([caracteristiques,c],ignore_index=True)

for i in tqdm(range(2005,2017+1)):
    read_year(i)
In [15]:
df = pd.merge(usagers,vehicules, on=["Num_Acc","num_veh"] ,how="inner")
df = pd.merge(df,lieux,on="Num_Acc",how="inner")
df = pd.merge(df,caracteristiques,on="Num_Acc",how="inner")

def missing_data(data):
    total = data.isnull().sum().sort_values(ascending = False)
    percent = (data.isnull().sum()/data.isnull().count()*100).sort_values(ascending = False)
    return pd.concat([total, percent], axis=1, keys=['Total NaN Values', 'Percentage of NaN Values'])

It looks like we have quite a lot of missing data , especially in these ones

  • adr : Postal address: variable filled in for accidents occurring in built-up areas
  • gps : GPS coding: 1 originator character:
  • lat : Latitude
  • long : Longitude
  • V1: Numeric index of the route number (example: 2 bis, 3 ter etc.)
  • V2: Letter alphanumeric index of the road
  • pr: Home PR number (upstream terminal number)
  • pr1: Distance in meters to the PR (relative to the upstream terminal)

Luckily we can get rid of them since they don't seem that important ( adr , gps , lat and long are highly correlated to com and dep )

Conclusion¶

First our modelling has provided us with some good insight over what makes the number of accidents go up

what determines most the damage done to the user by an accident is the place that the user occupies during the accident followed by the type of collision followed by the type of vehicule followed by the commune

So where you live actually impacts your chance of being in an accident

Then we provided a proof of concept for a predicting solution of the number of accidents , that can be used to determine how much stuff is needed on special days and if the ambulances should be on alert state.
